WEBVTT

00:04.738 --> 00:05.806 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:05.839 --> 00:06.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:06.840 --> 00:08.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And I'm Hari
Sreenivasan.

00:08.508 --> 00:10.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On the "NewsHour"
tonight:
Donald Trump's attack on the
integrity of

00:10.978 --> 00:17.451 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
U.S. elections has both
Democrats and Republicans
coming to the defense of a
pillar of democracy.

00:17.484 --> 00:22.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Then: a ground
report from
swing state North Carolina --
how Americans

00:22.589 --> 00:25.459 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
struggling with poverty in rural
areas view
this election.

00:25.492 --> 00:30.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK TRUDELL, North Carolina: I
mean, if they
came down here and saw how
people are actually

00:30.530 --> 00:35.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
living in rural America, then
maybe they would
change it.

00:35.535 --> 00:37.337 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Maybe they would do something.

00:37.371 --> 00:42.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And the
surprising split over
a proposed carbon tax in
Seattle, Washington,

00:42.910 --> 00:46.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
putting residents in a dead heat
over how
to keep the state green.

00:46.280 --> 00:50.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL BRUNE, Executive
Director, Sierra
Club: Two of the biggest
challenges we face

00:50.083 --> 00:55.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in this country are climate
change and economic
inequality.

00:55.555 --> 01:00.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If we pit one of those
challenges against
the other, neither will be
successful.

01:00.794 --> 01:03.664 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All that and
more on tonight's
"PBS NewsHour."

01:03.697 --> 01:08.135 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:08.168 --> 01:20.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On this day
after the final
debate, Donald Trump is at the
center of a

01:20.147 --> 01:22.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
political storm again.

01:22.115 --> 01:26.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It blew up last night with his
refusal to
say he'd acknowledge next
month's outcome.

01:26.787 --> 01:32.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
I will totally accept the
results of this

01:32.225 --> 01:39.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
great and historic presidential
election,
if I win.

01:39.866 --> 01:41.668 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

01:41.702 --> 01:45.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Donald Trump
in Delaware,
Ohio, today, stirring the pot
again on what

01:45.906 --> 01:47.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
happens if he loses.

01:47.674 --> 01:54.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Of course, I would
accept a
clear election result, but I
would also reserve

01:54.081 --> 02:01.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my right to contest or file a
legal challenge
in the case of a questionable
result.

02:01.421 --> 02:07.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All of that
after the nominee
touched off a furor during his
final debate

02:07.594 --> 02:09.496 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with Hillary Clinton.

02:09.529 --> 02:11.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS WALLACE, Moderator: Are
you saying you're
not prepared now to commit to
that principle?

02:11.131 --> 02:13.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: What I'm saying is
that I will
tell you at the time.

02:13.433 --> 02:14.401 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I will keep you in suspense.

02:14.434 --> 02:16.370 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK?

02:16.403 --> 02:17.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate:
Well, Chris, let me respond to
that, because

02:17.137 --> 02:19.139 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's horrifying.

02:19.172 --> 02:22.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Clinton went
further post-debate
while flying from Las Vegas
early this morning.

02:22.943 --> 02:28.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: So, what
he said tonight
is part of his whole effort to
blame somebody

02:28.215 --> 02:31.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
else for his campaign and for
where he stands
in this election.

02:31.351 --> 02:35.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Trump also got
pushback
from fellow Republicans,
including John Thune,

02:35.956 --> 02:38.258 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the number three Republican in
the Senate.

02:38.291 --> 02:43.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said all such talk -- quote
-- "undermines
an electoral system that is a
model for nations

02:43.263 --> 02:44.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
around the world."

02:45.032 --> 02:48.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another Republican senator, Bob
Corker, who
has campaigned with Trump,
tweeted: "It is

02:48.902 --> 02:53.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
imperative that Donald Trump
clearly state
that he will accept the
results."

02:53.573 --> 02:56.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senate Majority Leader Mitch
McConnell declined
comment today.

02:56.476 --> 03:00.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And House Speaker Paul Ryan's
office said
he is fully confident the states
will carry

03:00.847 --> 03:02.916 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
out this election with
integrity.

03:02.949 --> 03:07.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, late today, President Obama
weighed in,
stumping for Clinton in Miami.

03:07.487 --> 03:09.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
That is not a joking matter.

03:09.756 --> 03:12.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No, no, no, I want everybody to
pay attention
here.

03:12.692 --> 03:20.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That is dangerous, because when
you try to
sow the seeds of doubt in
people's minds about

03:20.567 --> 03:23.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the legitimacy of our elections,
that undermines
our democracy.

03:23.970 --> 03:28.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Meanwhile, in
New York,
another woman came forward to
accuse Donald

03:28.875 --> 03:30.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Trump of groping her.

03:30.310 --> 03:35.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Karena Virginia says it happened
in New York
in 1998.

03:35.215 --> 03:38.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Trump today accused Clinton
of political
cheating.

03:38.151 --> 03:42.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He cited a hacked e-mail that
showed she was
tipped about a death penalty
question during

03:42.989 --> 03:44.724 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a primary season town hall.

03:44.758 --> 03:47.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: That is cheating
at the highest
level.

03:47.961 --> 03:52.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: As for last
night's final
face-off, early ratings show
about 68 million

03:52.699 --> 03:57.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Americans watched, more than the
second debate,
but far fewer than the first.

03:57.070 --> 04:02.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, both candidates share a
stage again,
this time, at the gala Al Smith
Dinner in

04:02.042 --> 04:03.810 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
New York.

04:03.844 --> 04:08.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In the day's
other news: A
Russia-Syrian humanitarian pause
took effect

04:08.315 --> 04:11.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Syria in the besieged city of
Aleppo.

04:11.518 --> 04:14.020 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It could run as long as four
days.

04:14.054 --> 04:19.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Using loudspeakers, the Syrian
military urged
residents to leave and gunmen to
lay down

04:19.159 --> 04:20.127 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their weapons.

04:20.160 --> 04:22.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Syrian army also dropped
leaflets.

04:22.195 --> 04:25.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the U.N.'s special envoy
said he doubts
the effort will work.

04:25.999 --> 04:28.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STAFFAN DE MISTURA, Special
United Nations
Envoy for Syria: Certainly, my
feeling is

04:28.401 --> 04:34.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that, from what I'm hearing,
that the people
do not want to leave their
places.

04:34.407 --> 04:37.110 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They do not want to become
refugees.

04:37.144 --> 04:39.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They want to stay in their
place.

04:39.112 --> 04:44.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they do request, stop the
bombings, which
needs to be, by the way, from
both sides.

04:44.184 --> 04:48.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Meanwhile, a
separate fight
north of Aleppo.

04:48.255 --> 04:53.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Turkey attacked Syrian Kurds
who've been fighting
Islamic State forces.

04:53.193 --> 04:58.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Military footage showed
airstrikes on Kurdish
fighters linked to a group the
U.S. supports.

04:58.698 --> 05:02.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Turkey says they're also tied to
militants
fighting the Turkish government.

05:02.402 --> 05:06.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In Iraq, the
battle for
Mosul claimed its first American
casualty,

05:06.473 --> 05:09.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a soldier killed by a roadside
bomb.

05:09.075 --> 05:13.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. forces are advising Iraqis
in their campaign
to retake the city from the
Islamic State.

05:13.346 --> 05:16.183 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
First, they have to capture
outlying towns.

05:16.216 --> 05:20.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And John Irvine of Independent
Television
News reports on the harrowing
trip of one

05:20.353 --> 05:22.189 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
such unit.

05:22.222 --> 05:27.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN IRVINE: A new day brought a
fresh assault,
and taking the fight I.S. for
the first time,

05:27.227 --> 05:32.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where Iraq special forces came
to quickly
make their mark.

05:32.933 --> 05:37.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The attack was a pincer
movement, and we were
in the lead vehicle with a team
of (INAUDIBLE)

05:37.671 --> 05:41.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who had to find safe passage
through the land
mines.

05:41.775 --> 05:46.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Two led the way on foot, but
soon came under
sniper fire.

05:46.980 --> 05:51.818 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
A gunship was called in.

05:51.851 --> 05:54.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The sniping was ended.

05:54.321 --> 05:59.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The explosives experts called
for a tank to
join them before leaving the
Kalamoff (ph)

05:59.492 --> 06:03.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Road and on to the safer ground
that is the
countryside.

06:03.563 --> 06:10.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were venturing into the
so-called caliphate,
and the Iraqi forces put down a
lot of suppressing

06:10.103 --> 06:11.871 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fire.

06:11.905 --> 06:17.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the telltale pings on our
vehicle indicated
that I.S. were still putting up
a night.

06:17.611 --> 06:22.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're coming under sniper fire
and firing
back.

06:22.449 --> 06:28.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's the problem with being in
the lead
vehicle in an offensive which
right now is

06:28.421 --> 06:30.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
pretty slow-going.

06:30.257 --> 06:38.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Later, the special forces fired
on a saloon
car which had overturned
speeding down a road.

06:38.632 --> 06:43.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When nothing happened, we
wondered if the
driver had been an innocent just
trying to

06:43.069 --> 06:45.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
flee the battlefield.

06:45.839 --> 06:53.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No, he was a suicide bomber who
had missed
us.

06:53.580 --> 06:58.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were just glad that, at the
end of the
day, all of us and our battered
vehicle had

06:58.318 --> 06:59.853 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
come through.

06:59.886 --> 07:14.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Only, it wasn't the end of the
day -- a fourth
car bomb attack on the convoy.

07:14.401 --> 07:20.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mosul is still a few days away
for Iraqi forces,
and the closer they get, the
harder it will

07:20.640 --> 07:21.808 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
become.

07:21.841 --> 07:25.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There are
5,000 U.S. troops
in Iraq.

07:25.245 --> 07:29.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
About 100 are embedded with
Iraqi and Kurdish
forces around Mosul.

07:29.249 --> 07:31.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will talk later to retired
General David
Petraeus.

07:31.584 --> 07:33.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He commanded U.S. troops in
Mosul in 2003.

07:33.920 --> 07:38.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The U.S. military
confirms
that North Korea test-fired
another ballistic

07:38.825 --> 07:42.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
missile overnight, but it
crashed shortly
after launch.

07:42.329 --> 07:45.131 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's the second failed test
since Saturday.

07:45.165 --> 07:50.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It came hours after the U.S. and
South Korea
agreed to strengthen military
and diplomatic

07:50.537 --> 07:52.472 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
efforts against the North.

07:52.505 --> 07:56.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The president
of the Philippines,
Rodrigo Duterte, announced today
what he calls

07:56.042 --> 08:01.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a separation from the U.S.
Duterte spoke in
Beijing after meeting with
Chinese President

08:01.981 --> 08:05.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Xi Jinping and signing a major
commercial
deal.

08:05.352 --> 08:10.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Afterward, he said that in
military and economic
terms, America has lost.

08:10.657 --> 08:16.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RODRIGO DUTERTE, Philippine
President: Maybe
I will also go to Russia to talk
to Putin

08:16.963 --> 08:24.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and tell him that there are
three of us against
the world, China, Philippines
and Russia.

08:24.104 --> 08:25.872 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

08:25.905 --> 08:29.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Duterte also
said he will
work with Xi to settle their
maritime dispute

08:29.542 --> 08:31.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the South China Sea.

08:31.311 --> 08:34.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In Washington, the State
Department called
the comments baffling and said
it will seek

08:34.681 --> 08:36.416 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
an explanation.

08:36.449 --> 08:40.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A super typhoon
blasted the
Northern Philippines overnight
with winds

08:40.520 --> 08:42.622 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of 140 miles an hour.

08:42.655 --> 08:47.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the most powerful storm
to hit the
country in three years, but the
death toll

08:47.093 --> 08:49.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of seven was far lower than
feared.

08:49.863 --> 08:53.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The storm did trigger flooding,
landslides
and power outages.

08:53.967 --> 08:57.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nearly 100,000 people had been
evacuated ahead
of time.

08:57.570 --> 09:03.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The European
Space Agency
now says its latest Mars lander
may have crashed.

09:03.510 --> 09:07.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ground controllers lost contact
with the experimental
probe yesterday as it dropped
toward the surface.

09:07.881 --> 09:12.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Animation showed how the lander
was supposed
to use a parachute and thrusters
to make a

09:12.852 --> 09:14.287 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
soft landing.

09:14.320 --> 09:18.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Europe's last attempt at a Mars
landing also
failed back in 2003.

09:18.158 --> 09:23.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On Wall Street,
stocks closed
lower, giving up yesterday's
modest gains.

09:23.129 --> 09:27.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Dow Jones industrial average
lost 40 points
to close at 18162.

09:27.667 --> 09:33.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Nasdaq fell four, and the
S&amp;P 500 slipped
nearly three.

09:33.506 --> 09:36.609 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And for wine
lovers, it's
a case of sour grapes.

09:36.643 --> 09:41.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A global survey out today finds
this year's
production is the lowest since
2012.

09:41.147 --> 09:45.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Floods, drought and other bad
weather took
a toll across Europe and South
America.

09:45.718 --> 09:49.322 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Wine output in the U.S. actually
went up slightly.

09:49.355 --> 09:53.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
an in-depth
look at some of the key moments
from last

09:53.259 --> 09:59.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
night's debate; rural voters
feeling abandoned
by today's politicians; General
David Petraeus'

09:59.199 --> 10:05.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
take on the fight in Mosul;
Washington state
divided over a tax on carbon
pollution; and

10:05.371 --> 10:09.409 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
much more.

10:09.442 --> 10:20.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As we heard
earlier, Donald
Trump continued to suggest today
that he might

10:20.720 --> 10:25.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not accept the results of the
November election
if he doesn't win.

10:25.425 --> 10:29.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But should he lose, could Trump
legally challenge
the results?

10:29.596 --> 10:31.498 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And how would that process work?

10:31.531 --> 10:35.201 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
To examine some of these
questions, we are
joined now by Chris Ashby.

10:35.235 --> 10:37.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's a Republican election
lawyer.

10:37.904 --> 10:42.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And Beverly Gage, she's
professor of American
history at Yale University.

10:42.809 --> 10:44.744 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you to
the program.

10:44.777 --> 10:45.845 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Beverly Gage, to you first.

10:45.879 --> 10:48.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Have we ever seen anything quite
like this
before?

10:48.147 --> 10:52.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE, Yale University:
We have not
seen anything like this before,
Judy.

10:52.919 --> 10:55.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There have been contested
elections in the
past.

10:55.788 --> 11:00.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those are often close
elections, where,
once the results are in, they
seem uncertain,

11:00.860 --> 11:03.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and so you have a variety of
appeals.

11:03.062 --> 11:09.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have never had a major
party candidate
say this far in advance that the
only legitimate

11:09.669 --> 11:12.805 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
outcome of only an election is
his own victory.

11:12.839 --> 11:14.507 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That is unprecedented.

11:14.541 --> 11:18.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, as you say,
we have had
contested elections after the
fact.

11:18.811 --> 11:25.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we certainly -- everyone who
is at least
of a certain age remembers 2000,
Bush v. Gore.

11:25.118 --> 11:27.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there have been others in
American history,
haven't there?

11:27.453 --> 11:32.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE: Right, there have
been contested
elections and really fiercely
fought elections

11:32.225 --> 11:37.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with a lot of bad feelings
almost since the
beginning of the republic.

11:37.196 --> 11:42.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What those have always produced
is, with one
pretty big exception, is the
peaceful transition

11:42.535 --> 11:44.370 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of power.

11:44.404 --> 11:48.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That exception, of course, is
1860, where
much of the white South said
that they wouldn't

11:48.975 --> 11:54.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
accept Abraham Lincoln's
election as president,
and we got the Civil War as a
result.

11:54.581 --> 12:01.487 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But with that pretty big
exception, everyone,
despite challenges, has
ultimately come around.

12:01.521 --> 12:07.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other than 2000, probably the
famous one in
recent memory was 1960, which
was this squeaker

12:07.393 --> 12:14.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of an election between Kennedy
and Nixon,
in which Nixon to some degree
challenged the

12:14.500 --> 12:16.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
election, but himself stepped
aside.

12:16.502 --> 12:19.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we know there
was a dispute
about that one.

12:19.038 --> 12:22.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chris Ashby, let me just play
devil's advocate
here, because what Donald Trump
is saying

12:22.842 --> 12:27.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- and he said this today -- he
said, I want
to reserve the right to file a
challenge in

12:27.347 --> 12:30.383 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
case of a questionable result.

12:30.416 --> 12:32.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is that not a reasonable thing
for him to
do?

12:32.185 --> 12:34.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS ASHBY, GOP Campaign
Lawyer: No, it's
not because it's a statement of
the obvious.

12:34.520 --> 12:36.289 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He doesn't waive his right.

12:36.322 --> 12:38.257 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He doesn't need to claim that
right now.

12:38.291 --> 12:42.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What he should do is say what
every major,
indeed every presidential
candidate before

12:42.895 --> 12:44.631 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
him has said, which is, I will
accept the
outcome.

12:44.664 --> 12:49.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, after the election, if
there is
some evidence that an election
of electors

12:49.836 --> 12:52.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in a particular state was
tainted by fraud,
then he could pursue that.

12:52.839 --> 12:57.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But by saying it now, he's
undermining the
legitimacy of this election and
the individuals

12:57.877 --> 12:59.112 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
who it elects.

12:59.145 --> 13:01.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's very dangerous and it's
destructive
to the country.

13:01.581 --> 13:07.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let's talk
for a moment
about what would it take to
trigger a challenge.

13:07.353 --> 13:14.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How off would the results have
to be in order
to -- for there to be warranted
a legitimate

13:14.594 --> 13:16.462 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
challenge to the results?

13:16.496 --> 13:20.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /CHRIS ASHBY: Well, the
standard here
in a challenge would be a
significant number

13:20.967 --> 13:23.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of votes that could be proven,
right?

13:23.736 --> 13:26.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can't just say that there
was generally
fraud.

13:26.172 --> 13:30.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have to know how many votes
either from
fraud or by mistake.

13:30.443 --> 13:33.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it has to be enough votes to
cover the
margin between the candidates.

13:33.780 --> 13:37.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, if you think that you
have to go out
and actually get this evidence,
you have to

13:37.350 --> 13:41.854 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
find voters, you have to
election records,
and you have to quantify this,
and you have

13:41.888 --> 13:44.524 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to do it in a time period of
about a month.

13:44.557 --> 13:48.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The election would have to be
pretty close
in order for them to have any
chance of quantifying

13:48.728 --> 13:50.129 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a difference between the two
candidates.

13:50.163 --> 13:53.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, when you say
pretty close,
how close do you mean?

13:53.700 --> 13:57.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /CHRIS ASHBY: Maybe a few
hundred,
maybe in the low thousands of
folks.

13:57.170 --> 13:58.271 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And even that would be a high
bar.

13:58.304 --> 14:00.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we're talking
state by
state.

14:00.239 --> 14:04.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /CHRIS ASHBY: That's
right, because
the contest is not of the
presidential election.

14:04.177 --> 14:05.578 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's of the electors.

14:05.611 --> 14:09.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that happens in 51 different
states and
the District of Columbia.

14:09.849 --> 14:13.553 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so you are bringing a
contest to the election
of the electors.

14:13.586 --> 14:18.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you would have to bring
enough state contests
to cover the difference in the
Electoral College.

14:18.491 --> 14:23.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if this election heads the
way that it
appears that it's heading, that
could be hundreds

14:23.396 --> 14:27.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of electoral votes that we need
to swing in
a contest decided by multiple
states at once.

14:27.667 --> 14:29.535 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a very, very high bar.

14:29.569 --> 14:34.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Beverly Gage,
back to what
we have seen historically in
American elections,

14:34.540 --> 14:39.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what's an example of a time when
-- I mean,
you can talk about 1960, 2000.

14:39.345 --> 14:45.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, dig a little bit deeper
into what
it would take to trigger
something and then

14:45.518 --> 14:46.486 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to pursue it.

14:46.519 --> 14:48.421 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BEVERLY GAGE: Right.

14:48.454 --> 14:53.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, one thing to note about
the 20th century,
for the most part, we haven't
had particularly

14:53.226 --> 14:55.128 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
close presidential elections.

14:55.161 --> 15:00.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Chris is right, that it
would need to
be incredibly close for anything
like this

15:00.066 --> 15:01.768 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to happen.

15:01.801 --> 15:05.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's actually fairly
unusual, though
we have gotten a little bit more
used to it

15:05.104 --> 15:06.739 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in recent years.

15:06.773 --> 15:11.711 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, 1960 was really a razor-thin
count.

15:11.744 --> 15:18.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, at that point, Nixon didn't
concede overnight,
but he did concede in the
morning.

15:18.084 --> 15:24.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Republican Party itself,
however, went
ahead and challenged various
election results

15:24.257 --> 15:27.059 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in states like Illinois, in
Texas.

15:27.093 --> 15:29.195 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sometimes, that was through the
courts.

15:29.228 --> 15:30.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sometimes, that was through
recounts.

15:31.030 --> 15:35.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there was never any truth
that there had
been any fraud significant
enough to change

15:35.935 --> 15:37.670 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the outcome of the election.

15:37.703 --> 15:42.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Nixon himself actually
always took it
as a point of political pride
that, though

15:42.175 --> 15:48.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he harbored a heavy heart in
that moment,
he in fact conceded to Kennedy
for the good

15:48.915 --> 15:50.650 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the country.

15:50.683 --> 15:56.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Chris Ashby,
let's talk
for a moment about 2004, Ohio,
John Kerry.

15:56.389 --> 16:02.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Democrats challenged some of
how that
state, the state of Ohio came
out.

16:02.428 --> 16:06.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It went for Bush in 2004, but
there were questions
raised.

16:06.332 --> 16:08.134 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /CHRIS ASHBY: Sure.

16:08.167 --> 16:11.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they raised those questions
in Congress,
and Congress disposed of those
questions pretty

16:11.070 --> 16:12.839 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
quickly.

16:12.872 --> 16:18.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the absence of some kind of
compelling
evidence of fraud or of mistakes
in the conduct

16:18.077 --> 16:22.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the election that affects the
outcome,
I just don't see people having
much patience

16:22.348 --> 16:25.117 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or time for this type of a
challenge.

16:25.151 --> 16:27.220 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The other
question, Chris Ashby
-- and we have discussed this on
the program

16:27.253 --> 16:31.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
earlier this week -- Donald
Trump is saying
to his supporters -- and he's
said this in

16:31.724 --> 16:38.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
several different parts of the
country -- you
need to go and watch what's
happening at polling

16:38.231 --> 16:39.198 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
places.

16:39.232 --> 16:40.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What would that mean, if that
happened?

16:41.000 --> 16:44.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /CHRIS ASHBY: Well, that's
a very
dangerous situation, because, in
most states,

16:44.103 --> 16:45.805 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they're not going to be allowed
in.

16:45.838 --> 16:49.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Most states require poll
watchers to have
some sort of credential, some
type of training

16:49.942 --> 16:52.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and potentially understanding of
the process
that they're observing.

16:52.645 --> 16:57.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even in those states where any
member of the
public can walk in and observe,
they're not

16:57.350 --> 17:01.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to get anywhere near a
voter, anywhere
near a poll booth, anywhere near
an election

17:01.487 --> 17:03.289 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
official.

17:03.322 --> 17:06.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if they try to interfere
with the conduct
of the election, they're going
to be removed.

17:06.392 --> 17:10.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when they either can't get
in or are taken
out, I think that's just going
to feed right

17:10.296 --> 17:12.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the suspicion that led them
there in
the first place.

17:12.899 --> 17:16.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now you play this out in
polling places
across the country, and you
broadcast it on

17:16.402 --> 17:21.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the news, and it gets picked up
on the Internet,
it's a very, very flammable
situation on Election

17:21.407 --> 17:23.142 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Day.

17:23.175 --> 17:27.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, Beverly
Gage, remind
us what it means in our
democracy that we

17:27.079 --> 17:31.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are able to count on and respect
the results
of our elections.

17:31.517 --> 17:37.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE: One of the most
important things
really since our founding has
been the peaceful

17:37.556 --> 17:38.958 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
transition of power.

17:38.991 --> 17:43.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is something that every
president has really
prided himself on.

17:43.362 --> 17:49.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you think back to the
founders, those
were people with a living memory
of revolution.

17:49.568 --> 17:51.337 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They had seen it in Europe.

17:51.370 --> 17:56.108 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They had experienced it
themselves, and they
understood that it was
absolutely critical

17:56.142 --> 18:00.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to affirm the electoral system
and to see
that power could pass
peacefully.

18:00.947 --> 18:06.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was one of the great
points of pride
for the country and has been
almost always

18:06.152 --> 18:07.920 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ever since.

18:07.954 --> 18:10.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And this is
another moment
for us to think about that and
remember what

18:10.890 --> 18:14.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it does mean for our country and
for our system
of government.

18:14.961 --> 18:17.496 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Beverly Gage, Chris Ashby, we
thank you both.

18:17.530 --> 18:18.798 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /CHRIS ASHBY: Thank you.

18:18.831 --> 18:20.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BEVERLY GAGE: Thanks.

18:20.700 --> 18:23.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Unlike the
first two debates,
last night, we heard a lot more
about policy

18:23.269 --> 18:24.470 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from both candidates.

18:24.503 --> 18:27.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here to help break them down is
our own Lisa
Desjardins.

18:27.173 --> 18:32.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the first exchanges that
was substantive
was about Supreme Court nominee
decisions

18:32.678 --> 18:37.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that these -- one of these two
presidents,
in whoever wins, would have and
what kind

18:37.883 --> 18:42.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of impact that person would have
in the courts
and on cases like Roe v. Wade.

18:42.421 --> 18:44.190 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Here's a clip.

18:44.223 --> 18:46.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
Based on what she's saying, and
based on where

18:46.058 --> 18:50.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
she's going, and where she's
been, you can
take the baby and rip the baby
out of the

18:50.997 --> 18:55.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
womb in the ninth month on the
final day.

18:55.201 --> 18:56.435 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's not acceptable.

18:56.469 --> 18:59.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How many
late-term abortions
are there?

18:59.238 --> 19:02.375 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Because it usually gets
distilled down into
these worse-case scenarios.

19:02.408 --> 19:04.210 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.

19:04.243 --> 19:06.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention
is really a good -- the best
resource we have

19:06.712 --> 19:07.947 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for these kinds of statistics.

19:07.980 --> 19:10.316 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But we only know after 21 weeks.

19:10.349 --> 19:11.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's what they say.

19:11.784 --> 19:17.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the U.S., roughly 1.3 percent
of all abortions
happen after 21 weeks.

19:17.189 --> 19:21.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's considered late term, but
it's still
the middle of the second
trimester.

19:21.060 --> 19:23.763 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That translates into about 6,100
abortions.

19:23.796 --> 19:26.198 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That was in 2012.

19:26.232 --> 19:29.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That is out of almost 700,000.

19:29.702 --> 19:31.037 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So it's a small percentage.

19:31.070 --> 19:32.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What is
Hillary Clinton's
position on this?

19:32.905 --> 19:34.707 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right.

19:34.740 --> 19:38.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
