source we can
use to make those investments?

48:40.985 --> 48:44.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREGORY MANKIW: If you give
people the right
incentives, then the private
sector will be

48:44.388 --> 48:45.723 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
smart enough to make the right
investments.

48:45.756 --> 48:49.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL BRUNE: Putting a price
on carbon can
be great policy.

48:49.593 --> 48:51.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that's not all that's
needed.

48:51.095 --> 48:54.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We need to find a way to address
the constituencies
in a particular state.

48:54.765 --> 49:01.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: How do you respond
to the criticism
that you're essentially catering
to certain

49:01.639 --> 49:06.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
constituencies here, rather than
independently
analyzing?

49:06.911 --> 49:08.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL BRUNE: That seems a
little silly.

49:08.879 --> 49:14.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's fair to say that
two of the biggest
challenges we face in this
country are climate

49:14.752 --> 49:18.122 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
change and economic inequality.

49:18.155 --> 49:23.360 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If we pit one of those
challenges against
the other, neither will be
successful.

49:23.394 --> 49:29.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But will anything
be successful,
asks Greg Mankiw, if we try to
address both

49:29.166 --> 49:31.735 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of those and more in one
package?

49:31.769 --> 49:36.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREGORY MANKIW: People on the
left say they
want to combine a carbon tax
with all their

49:36.941 --> 49:38.676 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
pro-spending agenda.

49:38.709 --> 49:41.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Someone on the far right could
say, gee, I
love a carbon tax, as long as we
use it to

49:41.111 --> 49:42.847 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
reduce the estate tax.

49:42.880 --> 49:47.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what I-732 tries to do is,
it tries to
frame the issue relatively
narrowly, so we

49:47.918 --> 49:51.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can all come together and reach
a consensus
on this, rather than bundling it
together

49:51.755 --> 49:56.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with a lot of extraneous issues,
perhaps important
issues, but are extraneous to
the issue of

49:56.260 --> 49:58.095 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
putting a price on carbon.

49:58.128 --> 50:02.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Last word goes to
Yoram Bauman,
the world's foremost stand-up
economist, and,

50:02.700 --> 50:05.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
given his long environmental
track record,
perhaps its greenest.

50:05.803 --> 50:09.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YORAM BAUMAN: One of the things
that I love
about this policy is that it
does have potential

50:10.007 --> 50:11.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for bipartisan support.

50:11.876 --> 50:13.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not big government.

50:13.310 --> 50:14.778 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's not smaller government.

50:14.812 --> 50:17.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just, how do we make the
tax system fairer
and more sustainable?

50:18.015 --> 50:21.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's a powerful message that
hopefully we
can take around the country.

50:21.452 --> 50:26.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: How the voters of
Washington
state respond to the message
will be known

50:26.357 --> 50:27.691 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on November 8.

50:27.725 --> 50:35.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is "NewsHour" economics
correspondent
Paul Solman.

50:35.399 --> 50:44.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now to another
in our Brief
But Spectacular series, where we
ask interesting

50:44.108 --> 50:46.043 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
people to share their passions.

50:46.076 --> 50:50.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, casting director David
Rubin, who's
more than a hundred film
credits.

50:50.180 --> 50:54.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID RUBIN, Casting Director:
The most important
thing for an actor to bring to
the table is

50:54.418 --> 50:56.186 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
themselves, their own
idiosyncrasy.

50:56.220 --> 51:01.358 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so many actors get
preoccupied with what
they think the filmmaker is
looking for.

51:01.392 --> 51:05.796 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, frankly, what we're looking
for is them.

51:05.829 --> 51:12.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of my first jobs was working
on the production
staff of "Saturday Night Live."

51:12.970 --> 51:15.639 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I was a lowly production
assistant.

51:15.673 --> 51:20.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the last two seasons of
the original
cast, John Belushi, and Dan
Aykroyd, Gilda

51:20.978 --> 51:22.146 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Radner, Jane Curtin.

51:22.179 --> 51:25.015 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It was insane.

51:25.049 --> 51:27.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During my last season, it was
actually announced
that the show would not
continue.

51:28.018 --> 51:29.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we all kind of scrambled for
work.

51:29.586 --> 51:32.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I happened to meet the head
of casting
at NBC.

51:32.156 --> 51:33.324 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She was looking for an
assistant.

51:33.357 --> 51:34.425 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
She hired me.

51:34.458 --> 51:36.193 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It was kismet.

51:36.226 --> 51:39.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I first read a screenplay,
there are
sometimes very specific
descriptions of the

51:39.330 --> 51:41.265 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
characters.

51:41.298 --> 51:46.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the first thing that I do is
forget those
descriptions, because writers
write very specifically,

51:46.136 --> 51:50.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not for the casting director or
not for the
director, but for the studio
executive or

51:50.341 --> 51:52.176 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the financier.

51:52.209 --> 51:57.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you read in a script
"doctor 40s," the
temptation on the part of the
filmmaker might

51:57.781 --> 52:01.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be just to assume that it was a
white male
in their 40s or 50s.

52:01.952 --> 52:06.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why couldn't it be an Asian
person in their
30s?

52:06.390 --> 52:08.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why couldn't it be a little
person?

52:08.559 --> 52:10.294 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why couldn't it be a Latino?

52:10.327 --> 52:14.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Gender diversity, racial
diversity, all of
those things come into play in a
conversation

52:14.565 --> 52:18.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with a filmmaker when you are
bringing in
different approaches to a
particular character.

52:18.802 --> 52:23.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are several pioneers in
casting that
opened the doors to the process
in general.

52:23.741 --> 52:27.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this really happened after
the demise
of the studio system, when
studios no longer

52:27.945 --> 52:29.480 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
had actors under contract.

52:29.513 --> 52:32.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They needed people who were
going to direct
the casting process.

52:32.950 --> 52:37.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lynn Stalmaster was the first
independent
casting director in motion
pictures, who cast

52:37.621 --> 52:40.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
films like "West Side Story" and
"The Graduate."

52:40.624 --> 52:46.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They had searched far and wide
before Dustin
Hoffman, from relative
obscurity, got that

52:46.296 --> 52:47.698 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
role.

52:47.731 --> 52:50.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Marion Dougherty in New York was
doing the
same groundbreaking work.

52:50.801 --> 52:54.071 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was about casting people for
their idiosyncrasy.

52:54.104 --> 52:56.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The thing that keeps this job
fresh is the
variety.

52:56.974 --> 52:59.209 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have cast over a hundred
motion pictures.

52:59.243 --> 53:01.645 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When I look at my resume, I get
a little tired.

53:01.678 --> 53:05.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just like an actor doesn't want
to be typecast,
I don't want to be typecast in
casting.

53:05.115 --> 53:10.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, on the wall of my office,
there's a poster
of "The English Patient" very
near a poster

53:10.954 --> 53:13.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of "Harold &amp; Kumar Escape from
Guantanamo
Bay."

53:13.057 --> 53:18.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are some times when an
actor comes in,
and they give what they think is
a botched

53:18.695 --> 53:22.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
audition, they go off on their
lines, something
goes wrong in the scene.

53:22.399 --> 53:28.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And often those are the most
illuminating
additions to me, those kind of
organic moments

53:28.572 --> 53:32.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where an actor connects with a
character,
even though they may not even
realize that

53:32.743 --> 53:34.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they are doing it.

53:34.278 --> 53:39.550 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My name is David Rubin, and this
is my Brief
But Spectacular take on casting.

